        ],
        [
          "Higher Education",
          "E-Learning",
          "Learning-path recommender / path optimization framework using CRNN + Transformer + Reinforcement Learning (PPO)",
          "Personalized learning paths / tailored learning routes / intervention suggestions",
          "Empirical deployment reports 1,200 participants across 3 institutions; benchmark datasets also include large public educational datasets",
          "OULAD university courses, OLI Engineering Statics, ASSISTments math, EdNet online learning",
          "Student learning history data, timestamps, course progress, learning duration, interaction records, question/problem logs, skill labels, knowledge-point graph, student outcomes",
          "CRNN first extracts temporal embeddings from student behavior data; Transformer models knowledge-point associations using predefined graph; RL/PPO then optimizes path recommendations using predicted paths and reward signals",
          "Yes — recommendations are iteratively updated through PPO based on real learning data and reward signals such as completion rate and test score improvement; hourly recommendation updates are mentioned in deployment description",
          "temporal feature extraction from sequential logs; predefined knowledge graph; nightly batch feature extraction and hourly recommendation updates in empirical deployment; incremental learning setup mentioned",
          "Personalized learning routes, recommended paths, predicted knowledge gaps, intervention suggestions, dashboard-based path recommendations",
          "15% increase in completion rate and 12% improvement in average test score over baseline methods; empirical comparison also reports baseline vs CRNN framework on completion rate (68% to 83%) and test score (75.3 to 87.6)",
          "RL makes the recommendation layer explicit. The LMS plugin description on page 20 reinforces practical recommender deployment.",
          "Some reported empirical results are described in a broad framework-level way and are not always tightly tied to a clearly separated recommendation baseline; reliance on predefined knowledge graphs; possible demographic bias in training data; public-dataset experiments and empirical deployment are somewhat mixed in presentation"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    },
